      <h1 class="section-title">Key Episodes</h1>
      <p class="section-subtitle">The moments that define the Odyssey — and what to watch for in each</p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>If you're reading the Odyssey for the first time, these are the episodes that deserve your full attention. These scenes are where Homer's themes, storytelling technique, and moral questions come into sharpest focus. You'll find the poem's most famous moments here — and its most debated ones.</p>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">The Cyclops (Book 9)</h3>
      <p>The Cyclops episode is the most famous scene in the Odyssey, and for good reason: it's where Odysseus's cleverness and fatal pride collide in a single moment.</p>
      
      <p>Trapped in Polyphemus's cave, Odysseus tricks the one-eyed giant by calling himself "Nobody." When he blinds the Cyclops with a burning stake, Polyphemus screams that "Nobody" is hurting him — so the other Cyclopes ignore his cries. Brilliant.</p>
      
      <p>But then Odysseus can't help himself. As his ship pulls away to safety, he shouts his real name back at the blinded monster. That single act of hubris earns him Poseidon's wrath for the next ten years. Watch how Homer frames this: Odysseus is telling this story to the Phaeacians, and his account of his own cleverness may be more self-serving than he admits.</p>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">The Underworld (Book 11)</h3>
      <p>This is the emotional and moral center of the entire poem. When Odysseus travels to the land of the dead, he meets the ghosts of fallen heroes — and what they tell him changes everything.</p>
      
      <p>Achilles, the greatest warrior of the Trojan War, delivers the most shocking line: he would rather be a slave among the living than king of all the dead. This directly challenges the heroic code of the Iliad. Glory in death? Achilles now says survival is worth more.</p>
      
      <p>Agamemnon warns Odysseus about treacherous wives — a shadow that hangs over Penelope for the rest of the story. And Ajax, still bitter over losing Achilles' armor to Odysseus, refuses to speak at all. His silence is a reminder: survival has costs that can never be repaid.</p>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">Odysseus and Penelope in the Firelight (Book 19)</h3>
      <p>This is the longest conversation in the Odyssey — and the most mysterious. Penelope sits by the fire, speaking at length to a beggar she does not recognize. Except the beggar is Odysseus, still in disguise.</p>
      
      <p>She tells him about the web she wove and unwove to delay the suitors. She describes a dream about an eagle killing her geese. She announces the contest of the bow. She weeps for her missing husband. And Odysseus, listening to all of this, consoles her and gives her false hope that Odysseus will return soon.</p>
      
      <p>Does she know it's him? Homer never tells us. The ambiguity is not a flaw — it's his most sophisticated move in the entire poem. Ask yourself as you read: what does Penelope understand, and when?</p>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">The Test of the Bow (Books 21–22)</h3>
      <p>Penelope sets the contest: whoever can string Odysseus's great bow and shoot an arrow through twelve axe-heads will win her hand in marriage. Not one of the suitors can even string it.</p>
      
      <p>Then the disguised beggar asks to try. The moment he picks up the bow — stringing it effortlessly, plucking the string like a lyre — every suitor in the room knows exactly what is about to happen.</p>
      
      <p>The slaughter that follows is brutal and efficient. Odysseus kills them all. It is justice, but Homer does not let it feel triumphant. The violence is necessary, but it is still violence. Notice how the poem lingers on the blood and the bodies.</p>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">The Recognition (Book 23)</h3>
      <p>Even after the suitors are dead, Penelope does not immediately accept that the stranger is her husband. She tests him with the secret of their marriage bed — built from a living olive tree rooted in the ground, immovable.</p>
      
      <p>Only the real Odysseus would know this. When he answers in anger at the suggestion the bed could be moved, she finally knows him. They weep together. But Homer does not end the scene with easy joy. Odysseus tells Penelope everything that is still to come: more trials, more journeys. The homecoming is not an ending. It is a resumption of a life together.</p>

